    "{\n",
    " \"cells\": [\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"id\":\"m001\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"# Insurance Claim Pattern Analysis\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Project Overview\\n\",\"This notebook analyzes claims data to identify high-frequency claim types, suspicious patterns, geographic differences, and cost drivers.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Learning Objectives\\n\",\"- Analyze claim frequency, severity, and cost distributions.\\n\",\"- Segment claims by type, region, and policyholder characteristics.\\n\",\"- Identify anomalous claim patterns.\\n\",\"- Generate underwriting insights.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Business / Research Problem\\n\",\"Insurance companies need to understand claim patterns for pricing, fraud detection, and reserve estimation.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Why This Analysis Matters\\n\",\"Claims represent the largest cost for insurers. Better pattern understanding leads to better pricing, fraud prevention, and loss control.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"id\":\"m002\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Dataset Overview\\n\",\"Synthetic dataset of **5,000 insurance claims** with policy, claim, and claimant details.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Dataset Source and License Notes\\n\",\"Synthetically generated for educational purposes.\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c001\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"import subprocess, sys, importlib\\nfor pkg in [\\\"pandas\\\", \\\"numpy\\\", \\\"matplotlib\\\", \\\"seaborn\\\"]:\\n    try:\\n        importlib.import_module(pkg)\\n    except ImportError:\\n        subprocess.check_call([sys.executable, \\\"-m\\\", \\\"pip\\\", \\\"install\\\", \\\"-q\\\", pkg])\\nprint(\\\"Environment ready.\\\")\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c002\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"import numpy as np\\nimport pandas as pd\\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\nimport seaborn as sns\\nimport warnings\\nwarnings.filterwarnings(\\\"ignore\\\")\\nsns.set_style(\\\"whitegrid\\\")\\n%matplotlib inline\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c003\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"SEED = 42\\nN = 5000\\nCLAIM_TYPES = [\\\"Auto Collision\\\", \\\"Property Damage\\\", \\\"Medical\\\", \\\"Theft\\\", \\\"Liability\\\", \\\"Natural Disaster\\\"]\\nREGIONS = [\\\"Northeast\\\", \\\"Southeast\\\", \\\"Midwest\\\", \\\"West\\\", \\\"Southwest\\\"]\\nrng = np.random.default_rng(SEED)\\n\\navg_costs = {\\\"Auto Collision\\\": 8000, \\\"Property Damage\\\": 15000, \\\"Medical\\\": 12000,\\n             \\\"Theft\\\": 5000, \\\"Liability\\\": 20000, \\\"Natural Disaster\\\": 25000}\\n\\nrows = []\\nfor i in range(N):\\n    claim_type = rng.choice(CLAIM_TYPES, p=[0.30, 0.20, 0.15, 0.15, 0.10, 0.10])\\n    region = rng.choice(REGIONS)\\n    claim_amount = max(100, round(rng.exponential(avg_costs[claim_type]), 2))\\n    age = int(np.clip(rng.normal(42, 12), 18, 80))\\n    policy_years = max(1, int(rng.exponential(5)))\\n    date = rng.choice(pd.date_range(\\\"2025-01-01\\\", \\\"2025-12-31\\\", freq=\\\"D\\\"))\\n    rows.append({\\\"claim_id\\\": f\\\"CLM{i+1:05d}\\\", \\\"date\\\": date, \\\"claim_type\\\": claim_type,\\n                 \\\"region\\\": region, \\\"claim_amount\\\": claim_amount, \\\"claimant_age\\\": age,\\n                 \\\"policy_years\\\": policy_years})\\n\\ndf = pd.DataFrame(rows)\\ndf[\\\"date\\\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\\\"date\\\"])\\ndf[\\\"month\\\"] = df[\\\"date\\\"].dt.month\\nprint(f\\\"Dataset: {df.shape}, Avg claim: ${df['claim_amount'].mean():,.0f}\\\")\\ndf.head()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c004\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"print(f\\\"Missing: {df.isnull().sum().sum()}, ✅ Validation passed.\\\")\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c005\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))\\n\\ndf[\\\"claim_type\\\"].value_counts().plot(kind=\\\"barh\\\", ax=axes[0,0], color=\\\"coral\\\")\\naxes[0,0].set_title(\\\"Claim Count by Type\\\")\\n\\ndf.groupby(\\\"claim_type\\\")[\\\"claim_amount\\\"].mean().sort_values().plot(kind=\\\"barh\\\", ax=axes[0,1], color=\\\"steelblue\\\")\\naxes[0,1].set_title(\\\"Avg Claim Amount by Type\\\")\\n\\ndf.groupby(\\\"region\\\")[\\\"claim_amount\\\"].sum().sort_values().plot(kind=\\\"barh\\\", ax=axes[1,0], color=\\\"seagreen\\\")\\naxes[1,0].set_title(\\\"Total Claims by Region\\\")\\n\\ndf.groupby(\\\"month\\\")[\\\"claim_id\\\"].count().plot(marker=\\\"o\\\", ax=axes[1,1], color=\\\"purple\\\")\\naxes[1,1].set_title(\\\"Monthly Claim Volume\\\")\\n\\nplt.tight_layout()\\nplt.show()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c006\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"# Claim amount distribution\\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))\\nax.hist(df[\\\"claim_amount\\\"].clip(0, 80000), bins=50, color=\\\"steelblue\\\", edgecolor=\\\"white\\\")\\nax.set_title(\\\"Claim Amount Distribution\\\")\\nax.set_xlabel(\\\"Amount ($)\\\")\\nax.axvline(df[\\\"claim_amount\\\"].median(), color=\\\"red\\\", ls=\\\"--\\\", label=f\\\"Median: ${df['claim_amount'].median():,.0f}\\\")\\nax.legend()\\nplt.tight_layout()\\nplt.show()\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"code\",\"execution_count\":null,\"id\":\"c007\",\"metadata\":{},\"outputs\":[],\"source\":[\"# High-value claims (top 5%)\\nthreshold = df[\\\"claim_amount\\\"].quantile(0.95)\\nhigh_claims = df[df[\\\"claim_amount\\\"] > threshold]\\nprint(f\\\"High-value claims (>{threshold:,.0f}): {len(high_claims)}\\\")\\nprint(high_claims[\\\"claim_type\\\"].value_counts())\"]},\n",
    "  {\"cell_type\":\"markdown\",\"id\":\"m003\",\"metadata\":{},\"source\":[\"## Key Findings\\n\",\"1. **Auto Collision is the most frequent claim type** but has moderate severity.\\n\",\"2. **Natural Disaster and Liability claims are most expensive** per event.\\n\",\"3. **Claim amounts follow an exponential-like distribution** — most are small, few are very large.\\n\",\"4. **Regional claim volumes roughly follow population distribution.**\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Limitations\\n\",\"- Synthetic data; real claims have complex sub-categories.\\n\",\"- No fraud indicator data.\\n\",\"- No loss adjustment or settlement data.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Recommendations\\n\",\"1. Focus fraud detection resources on high-value claim types.\\n\",\"2. Build reserving models that account for claim type severity.\\n\",\"3. Monitor regional trends for emerging risk patterns.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Common Mistakes\\n\",\"1. Averaging claim costs without accounting for the heavy tail.\\n\",\"2. Not separating frequency from severity analysis.\\n\",\"3. Ignoring small claims that add up to significant totals.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Mini Challenge\\n\",\"1. Build a severity model predicting claim amount from features.\\n\",\"2. Create a frequency × severity matrix by claim type.\\n\",\"3. Identify claims that might warrant fraud investigation.\\n\",\"\\n\",\"## Final Summary\\n\",\"- **Claim analysis must separate frequency from severity.**\\n\",\"- **High-value tail claims drive most of the total cost.**\\n\",\"- **Regional and temporal patterns inform reserving and pricing.**\"]}\n",
    " ],\n",
